{{POV|date=October 2018}} {{copyedit|date=October 2018}} {{Infobox website | name = Blim | logo =Blim logo.svg | logo_size = | logo_alt = | logo_caption = <!-- or: | logocaption = --> | screenshot = | collapsible = <!-- set as "on", "y", etc, otherwise omit/leave blank --> | collapsetext = <!-- collapsible area's heading (default "Screenshot"); omit/leave blank if collapsible not set --> | background = <!-- for collapsetext heading; default grey (gainsboro) --> | screenshot_size = | screenshot_alt = | caption = | url = {{URL|www.blim.com}} | slogan = | commercial = <!-- "Yes", "No" or leave blank --> | type = [[Public company|Public]] | registration = Required | language = Spanish | num_users = | content_license = <!-- or: | content_licence = --> | programming_language = | services = {{flatlist| *[[Film production]] *[[Film distribution]] *[[Television production]] }} | products = {{flatlist| *[[Streaming media]] *[[Video on demand]] }} | owner = [[Televisa|Televisa S.A. de C.V]] | author = <!-- or: creator / authors / creators --> | editor = <!-- or: | editors = --> | launch_date = {{start date and age|2016|2|22|df=yes}} | location_city = [[Mexico City]] | location_country = [[Mexico]] | alexa = <!-- {{increase}} {{steady}} {{decrease}} [http://www.alexa.com/siteinfo/example.com ##] (US/Global MM/YYYY) --> | ip = | issn = <!-- ISSN, e.g. 1085-6706 (automatically linked to http://www.WorldCat.org) --> | oclc = <!-- OCLC number, useful where an ISSN has not been allocated (automatically linked to http://www.WorldCat.org) --> | current_status = | footnotes = }}
'''''Blim''''' is an [[Video on demand|on-demand video]] subscription service, offered online via [[Televisa|Televisa S.A. de C.V]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Televisa lanza servicio de contenido bajo demanda|url=http://eleconomista.com.mx/industrias/2016/02/22/televisa-lanza-servicio-entretenimiento-bajo-demanda|website=eleconomista.com.mx|accessdate=7 May 2017|language=Spanish|date=February 22, 2016}}</ref> through an internet connection, which offers access to the programs for strictly personal use, in exchange for payment of the monthly subscription.<ref>{{cite web|title=Términos de uso|url=http://www.blim.com/site/terms-conditions|website=blim.com|accessdate=7 May 2017|language=Spanish}}</ref>
Its center of operations is in [[Mexico City]]. It is currently available in 17 countries: [[Mexico]], [[Colombia]], [[Argentina]], [[Costa Rica]], [[Panama]], [[Chile]], [[Peru]], [[Venezuela]], [[Ecuador]], [[Guatemala]], [[Bolivia]], [[Honduras]], [[Paraguay]], [[El Salvador]], [[Nicaragua]], [[Uruguay]], [[Belize City|Belize]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Televisa le entra a la competencia en "streaming"|url=http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/articulo/espectaculos/television/2016/02/22/televisa-le-entra-la-competencia-en-streaming|website=eluniversal.com.mx|publisher=El Universal México|accessdate=7 May 2017|language=Spanish}}</ref>
It owns productions of [[Televisa]], as well as titles of creators and distributors like [[Walt Disney Pictures]], [[Paramount Pictures]], [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]] and [[BBC]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Elias|first1=Irán|title=El imperio del streaming|url=https://www.elsiglodetorreon.com.mx/noticia/1225311.el-imperio-del-streaming.html|website=elsiglodetorreon.com.mx|publisher=El Siglo del Torreón México|accessdate=8 May 2017|language=Spanish|date=22 May 2016}}</ref>
To compete with other [[Video on demand|video services on demand]] initially offers the monthly subscription of $109 [[Mexican peso]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Conoce Blim, la nueva plataforma de contenidos en español|url=http://espectaculos.televisa.com/series/noticias/924137/blim-lanzamiento-plataforma-digital-series-streaming/|website=espectaculos.televisa.com|accessdate=8 May 2017|language=Spanish}}</ref>Like [[Netflix]], Blim offers the first free month of its service.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Gutiérrez|first1=Óscar|title=Todo lo que necesitas saber de Blim, el competidor mexicano de Netflix|url=https://www.cnet.com/es/noticias/blim-que-es-blim-netflix-precio-como-funciona-catalogo-memes/|website=cnet.com|accessdate=8 May 2017|language=Spanish|date=15 March 2016}}</ref>
==Controversy== In 2016, Televisa realized people watched more Netflix than cable television. To re-gain all their lost viewers, they decided to remove all its original content from [[Netflix]] in order to create its own Netflix-like streaming service, which was called Blim. Soon after Televisa announced Blim, the Mexicans started mocking Televisa through [[Internet meme|memes]] that strongly opinionated and mocked Televisa for producing lesser quality original content in comparison to the more critically acclaimed [[Netflix]] original content.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://yucatan.com.mx/espectaculos/breves-del-espectaculo/memes-se-lanzan-contra-blim|title=“Memes” se lanzan contra Blim - El Diario de Yucatán|website=yucatan.com.mx|accessdate=25 July 2017|language=Spanish}}</ref> [[Netflix]] itself released an ad which made fun of Televisa's original content, and criticized Bilm and Televisa for the perceived lesser quality of their content, as well as for removing their content from Netflix. The ad featured a man being sad because Televisa original content was removed, and his mom looking weird at him.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com.mx/netflix-se-burla-de-televisa-y-rebelde/#gs.EtJ8xNM|title=Netflix se burla de Televisa y Rebelde - Forbes Mexico|date=4 October 2016|publisher=|accessdate=25 July 2017|language=Spanish}}</ref> Televisa retaliated by releasing an ad, where a look-like man dressed the same as the man who was sad in Netflix's ad, was happy for buying Blim.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://regeneracion.mx/blim-intenta-burlarse-de-netflix-y-nada-sale-bien/|title=Blim intenta burlarse de Netflix y todo sale mal (VIDEO)|date=25 October 2016|publisher=|accessdate=25 July 2017|language=Spanish}}</ref> However Televisa's ad did not got the response it expected, because the ad only caused Televisa to get even more not favorable criticisms in comparison to Netflix. Causing Blim and Televisa to be even more heavily criticized for not understanding millennials,{{quotation needed|date=October 2018}} some which were as far as thanking Televisa for removing their content from Netflix. The main argument against Televisa, was people arguing there was no need to pay for a streaming service, in order to see series that are available to watch without even needing to buy cable in the first place.<ref>{{cite web|title=Dos semanas probando Blim|url=http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/blogs/alejandro-aleman/2016/03/11/dos-semanas-probando-blim|website=eluniversal.com.mx|accessdate=26 July 2017|language=Spanish}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sdpnoticias.com/enelshow/television/2016/02/22/blim-copia-de-netflix-fracasara-porque-televisa-no-entiende-a-los-mileniales|title=Blim, copia de Netflix, fracasará porque Televisa no entiende a los mileniales|date=22 February 2016|publisher=|accessdate=25 July 2017|language=Spanish}}</ref>
