{{Unreferenced stub|auto=yes|date=December 2009}}
'''Bläserklasse''' ("blowing class") is a [[Music education|musical education]] class which specialises in wind instruments, i.e. the [[woodwind]]s and [[Brass instrument|brass]]. All students spend usually at least 2 years studying an instrument, with the class forming a wind [[orchestra]] made up of an amalgamation of woodwind and brass instruments.

{{DEFAULTSORT:Blaserklasse}}
[[Category:Music education]]


{{Woodwind-instrument-stub}}

The '''British Heavy Middleweight Championship''' was a top [[Professional wrestling in the United Kingdom|British wrestling]] [[Championship (professional wrestling)|championship]] found throughout the country's circuit. The title's history dates back to its foundation by [[Joint Promotions]] in 1953. Officially heavy middleweights were required to weight between {{nowrap|12 st 8 lb}} {{nowrap|(176 lbs)}} and {{nowrap|13 st 5 lb}} {{nowrap|(187 lb)}}.<ref>Peter Bills, ''Wrestling'', David & Charles, 1983, p. 62</ref>
The championship was recognised and defended on matches screened by UK national television network [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] as part of the professional wrestling slot on ''[[World of Sport (UK TV series)|World of Sport]]'' as well as standalone broadcasts.<ref name=Sept78>{{cite news | title=Marty Jones capture of British Heavy Middleweight title from Mark Rocco in Woking 13 September 1978 | work= World Of Sport - Wrestling | publisher=[[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] | date= 23 September 1978 }}</ref><ref name=Oct71981>{{cite news | title=Alan Kilby capture of vacant British Heavy Middleweight title in tournament final over King Ben in Preston 7 October 1981 | work= World Of Sport - Wrestling | publisher= [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] | date=31 October 1981}}</ref><ref name=finlaybeatschic>{{cite news | title=Fit Finlay capture of British Heavy Middleweight title from Chic Cullen in Bradford 17 September 1987, | work=Professional Wrestling | publisher=[[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] | date=31 October 1987 }}</ref> Pre-publicity for these championship match broadcasts was given in ITV's nationally published listings magazine [[TVTimes]]<ref name=>{{cite web | url=http://johnlisterwriting.com/itvwrestling/78.html | title=Champion vs Champion: British Light-heavyweight champion Marty Jones v British Heavy-Middleweight champion Mark Rocco" | publisher=TVTimes | work= Saturday 23 September - Friday 29 September 1978 - Saturday listings page}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://johnlisterwriting.com/itvwrestling/81.html | publisher=TVTimes | title="For the vacant British Heavy Middleweight championship: Alan Kilby v King Ben" | work=Saturday 7 October - Friday 13 October 1981 - Saturday listings page}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://johnlisterwriting.com/itvwrestling/87.html | title="British Heavy Middleweight Championship: Chic Cullen v Fit Finlay" | publisher=TVTimes | work=Saturday 31 October - Friday 6 November 1987 - Saturday listings page}}</ref> The entire 31 October 1987 edition of the standalone ''Wrestling'' broadcast was given over to [[Fit Finlay]]'s recapture of the title from Chic Cullen in [[Bradford]], 17 September 1987<ref name=finlaybeatschic /> and highlights of this match were included on the official ITV wrestling compilation VHS release ''Mayhem and Mystery''.<ref>''Mayhem and Mystery'', The Video Collection, VC2181, 1991</ref> Similarly, highlights of [[Alan Kilby]]'s capture of the vacant title in a tournament final over King Ben in [[Preston, Lancashire|Preston]], 7 October 1981, were included on official ITV wrestling compilation DVD release ''The Best Of British Wrestling A-Z''. <ref>''The Best of British Wrestling A-Z'' (Bonus Feature: Forgotten Heroes) Granada Home Video 2006</ref>
== Title history == The title was founded in 1953 and remained in Joint Promotions until the mid-1980s when it was taken over by [[All Star Wrestling]]. The title remained active until the mid-1990s.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.wrestling-titles.com/europe/uk/bri-hm.html | title=British Heavy Middleweight Title | work=Wrestling-Titles.com | accessdate=May 22, 2017}}</ref>
{| border="1" cellpadding="1" |'''Wrestler:''' |'''Times:''' |'''Date:''' |'''Place:''' |'''Notes:''' |- |Eric Taylor |1 |1953 | |Vacated the title in 1966 when he left Joint Promotions.<ref name=BrHeavyMiddleweight>{{cite book|first1=Royal | last1=Duncan | first2=Gary | last2=Will | title=Wrestling title histories: professional wrestling champions around the world from the 19th century to the present | chapter=Europe - Great Britain: British Heavy Middleweight Title|page=403|publisher=Archeus Communications|location=Pennsylvania|year=2000|isbn=0-9698161-5-4}}</ref> |- |Bert Royal |1 |before 4 May 1966 | |<ref name=BrHeavyMiddleweight/> |- |Bert Royal |2 |16 January 1968 |[[Blackburn]] |Defeated Peter Preston, having lost the title at some point before this date.<ref name=BrHeavyMiddleweight/> |- |[[Jackie Pallo]] |1 |21 April 1969 |[[Nottingham]] |<ref name=BrHeavyMiddleweight/> |- |Bert Royal |3 |before May 1969 |N/A |<ref name=BrHeavyMiddleweight/> |- |Steve Logan |1 |29 August 1975 |[[Liverpool]] |<ref name=BrHeavyMiddleweight/> |- |Bert Royal |4 |11 November 1975 |[[Manchester]] |<ref name=BrHeavyMiddleweight/> |- |[[Mark Rocco]] |1 |11 June 1977 |Manchester |<ref name=BrHeavyMiddleweight/> |- |[[Marty Jones]] |1 |13 September 1978 |[[Woking]] |Jones, already the holder of the [[British Light Heavyweight Championship]], vacated the title immediately.<ref name=BrHeavyMiddleweight/> |- |Mark Rocco |2 |6 December 1978 |Blackburn |Won a tournament final against [[Chris Adams (wrestler)|Chris Adams]]. Vacated title in August 1981 after winning the world title.<ref name=BrHeavyMiddleweight/> |- |[[Alan Kilby]] |1 |7 October 1981 |Preston |Won a tournament for the belt, defeating King Ben in the final<ref name=BrHeavyMiddleweight/> |- |[[Dave Finlay]] |1 |9 June 1982 |[[Bath, Somerset|Bath]] |<ref name=BrHeavyMiddleweight/> |- |[[Alan Kilby]] |2 |before August 1982 | |<ref name=BrHeavyMiddleweight/> |- |[[Dave Finlay]] |2 |14 September 1982 |[[Croydon]] |<ref name=BrH